        "text": "WHITE OAK, Texas (KLTV) - With August temperatures expected to be in triple digits for the next week, it’s a dangerous time to be playing any sport outside.\n\nEast Texas high school football coaches have a challenge in trying to practice before the season begins.\n\nHeat danger has schools scheduling practices in the early mornings or late evening to avoid the hottest part of the day.\n\n“We can’t do a true two-a-days like they used to do. Especially with all the Wet Bulb guidelines that have got into play this year and everything else, finding those times in the day when we can get our kids moving like we want them to move,” says White Oak Roughneck head football coach Michael Ludlow.\n\nThat Wet Bulb is Wet Bulb Globe Temperature, or WBGT, to monitor conditions during outdoor physical activities. It estimates the effect of temperature, relative humidity, wind speed, and solar radiation using a combination of temperatures from three thermometers.\n\n“Simulating the game as much as we can in practice, but also keeping them hydrated, keeping them rested,” Ludlow said.\n\nCoaches must schedule practices at appropriate levels, measure ratio of workout time to time allotted for rest and hydration, and the levels at which activities should be ended.\n\n“This is the hottest day we’ve had so far, so we’ll have our tent set up and a port-o-cool. As a coach you always preach mental reps. I think it becomes even more important now, with the kids in the back not getting reps,” says Hawkins high school head football coach Bill Cowley.\n\nCoaches have to be creative about getting enough work in.\n\n“Every day is important, we preach to the kids all the time be up here. We’re right around the corner for that first game,” Cowley says.\n\n“We need to find those mental reps that we can get. Getting creative with Wet Bulb stuff, even within the guidelines they’ve set, you have to get creative to make sure you meet all the needs of those kids and prep them,” Coach Ludlow says.\n\nin 2023, the UIL approved WBGT as the recommended forecast measurement to be used to monitor conditions during outdoor physical activities."
